notes: Jeffrey J. Fenton served as Senior Vice President of Business Development at United Rentals from 2012 until his retirement in June 2022. He previously served as a director of Del Taco Restaurants Inc. (TACO) and is based in San Francisco. name: Muller, Richard A.
title: Professor of Physics Emeritus
notes: Richard A. Muller (born January 6, 1944) is an American physicist and Emeritus Professor of Physics at UC Berkeley, where he has been on the faculty since 1978. In 2010 he co-founded Berkeley Earth, an independent 501(c)(3) nonprofit addressing climate temperature record concerns. In 2016 he co-founded Deep Isolation, a private company pursuing nuclear waste disposal in deep boreholes. He received a MacArthur Foundation Prize Fellowship and other major awards.
ngos: Berkeley Earth (co-founder and scientific director, nonprofit); Berkeley Geochronology Center (board of directors); Institute for Nuclear and Particle Astrophysics (founding member, board of advisors)

name: Murray, Daniel Buntin

He has been actively involved in investment management and capital markets since 1995 and is also affiliated with D.B. Murray Capital Management LP in Belvedere, CA.

name: Nally, Patrick Louis
title: Chief Executive Officer
notes: Patrick Louis Nally (born 1947) is a British entrepreneur widely credited as the 'Founding Father' of modern sports marketing. He co-founded the West Nally Group in 1970, which pioneered sports sponsorship packaging for major events including the FIFA World Cup and Olympic Games. He is President of the International Federation of Match Poker (IFMP) and previously served the International Federation of Poker (IFP) since its founding in 2009.
ngos: International Federation of Match Poker (IFMP) - President; International Federation of Poker (IFP) - founding supporter

name: Newbigging, David K.
title: Former Tai-pan and Chairman, Jardine Matheson & Co.
notes: Sir David Kennedy Newbigging OBE (born January 19, 1934) is a British businessman who served as Tai-pan and Chairman/Senior Managing Director of Jardine Matheson & Co., the leading British trading firm in East Asia, from 1975 until his retirement in 1983. He was also an unofficial member of both the Executive Council and Legislative Council of Hong Kong. Post-retirement he served as chairman of Rentokil Group plc, Friends Provident, Thistle Hotels, Equitas Holdings, and several other companies. He was knighted in 2011 for voluntary service to cancer research.

name: Palm, Charles G.
title: Deputy Director Emeritus
notes: Charles G. Palm is Deputy Director Emeritus of the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, completing 31 years of service there including 18 years directing the Hoover Library and Archives. He was appointed by President George H.W. Bush to the National Historical Publications and Records Commission (1990-1996) and by Governor George Deukmejian to the California Heritage Preservation Commission (serving as chairman 1997-2004). He negotiated the landmark 1992 agreement to microfilm over 12 million pages of Soviet Communist Party archives.
ngos: Society of American Archivists (fellow); Society of California Archivists (past president); California Heritage Preservation Commission (chairman 1997-2004)

name: Perry, Mark W.

He was earlier a partner at Cooley LLP (1981-1994) and served as President and CEO of Aerovance, Inc. and Entrepreneur-in-Residence at Third Rock Ventures.

name: Ritter, Gordon Phillips

He was named to the Forbes Midas List in 2007, 2012, 2014, and 2015 and graduated from Princeton in 1986.

title: Director / Board Member
notes: Robert J. Swain is a Director of OYO Geospace Corporation (an international seismic instrumentation company) and a Board Member at the Hoover Institution at Stanford University. He founded Kinemetrics in October 1969, a major producer of seismological and earthquake engineering instrumentation with operations in over 80 countries, which was acquired by OYO Geospace in 1991. He earned a BSEE from Purdue University (1951) and began his career at GM's AC Electronics Division. He also chairs the Coalition of Professional and Scientific Associations supporting the National Earthquake Hazard Reduction Program.

name: Taylor, John Brian
title: Mary and Robert Raymond Professor of Economics; George P. Shultz Senior Fellow in Economics
notes: John Brian Taylor (born December 8, 1946) is an American economist best known for proposing the 'Taylor Rule' for monetary policy in 1993. He is the Mary and Robert Raymond Professor of Economics at Stanford University and a Senior Fellow at the Hoover Institution. He served as Under Secretary of the Treasury for International Affairs under President George W. Bush (2001-2005) and was senior policy advisor during the Bush 2000 presidential campaign. He was President of the Mont Pelerin Society from 2018 to 2020.
ngos: Hoover Institution Working Group on Economic Policy (chair); Hoover Technology, Economics and Governance Working Group (co-chair); Overseas Private Investment Corporation (board, 2001-2004); Independent Institute (board of advisors); Mont Pelerin Society (former president)
